───

Visual behavior
The terminal is rendered directly in the editor.
Example:
text
+----------------------+
| Hello                |
| World                |
|                      |
+----------------------+

If line numbers are enabled:
text
+----------------------+
| 1 | Hello            |
| 2 | World            |
|                      |
+----------------------+


───

Appending text
Characters are appended to the current cursor position.
text
.term:{
  append = ^41
  set = 1
}

Result:
text
A


───

Appending another character:
text
.term:{
  append = ^42
  set = 1
}

Result:
text
AB


───

Writing multiple characters
Values wider than 8 bits are interpreted as consecutive bytes.
text
.term:{
  append = ^414243
  set = 1
}

Result:
text
ABC


───

New line
Move the cursor to the next line.
text
.term:{
  newline = 1
  set = 1
}


───

Example:
text
.term:{
  append = ^48656C6C6F
  set = 1
}

.term:{
  newline = 1
  set = 1
}

.term:{
  append = ^576F726C64
  set = 1
}

Result:
text
Hello
World


───

Clear
Erase all terminal contents.
text
.term:{
  clear = 1
  set = 1
}

After clear:
text

(empty terminal)

───

Word wrap
When enabled:
text
wordWrap: 1

text automatically continues on the next line.
Example:
text
columns: 10

Appending:
text
HelloWorldABC

Produces:
text
HelloWorld
ABC


───

Scrolling
When the cursor reaches the last row, the terminal automatically scrolls upward.
Example:
text
rows: 3

Before:
text
Line1
Line2
Line3

Appending:
text
Line4

Produces:
text
Line2
Line3
Line4


───

Line numbers
Enable:
text
lineNumbers: 1

Display:
text
1 | Booting...
2 | CPU Ready
3 | Running

Line numbers are visual only.
They are not part of the stored text.

───

Cursor position
The terminal maintains an internal cursor.
The cursor automatically advances after each appended character.
Users cannot directly modify the cursor position in v1.

───

Runnable — Hello World
text
comp [terminal] .term:
  rows: 5
  columns: 20
  :

text
.term:{
  append = ^48656C6C6F20576F726C64
  set = 1
}

Display:
text
Hello World


───

Runnable — CPU output
text
comp [terminal] .console:
  rows: 10
  columns: 40
  :

text
.console:{
  append = acc
  set = printInstruction
}

Whenever:
text
printInstruction

becomes active, the accumulator value is appended to the terminal.

